sols_latex:
We compute the determinant of our matrix

\begin{align*}
\det(B) &= (a^2c + a^2b + a^2b - (a^3 + a^2c  + ab^2))\\ &= 2a^2b -a^3 - ab^2
\end{align*}

In order for the matrix to be invertible, we need the determinant to be
nonzero. For that, we need to factor our determinant

\begin{align*}
\det(B) &= 2a^2b -a^3 - ab^2\\ &= -a(a^{2} - 2ab  + b^{2}) \\ &= -a(a-b)^{2}
\end{align*}

So we obtain that

\begin{align*}
\displaystyle \det(B) = -a(a-b)^2
\end{align*}

and so, for the matrix to be invertible, that is, for the matrix not to
have a determinant of zero, we require that $a \neq 0$ and $a \neq b$.

statement_latex:
For which values of the parameters $\displaystyle a,b,c$ is the
